entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued November 13 at 1:26PM MST by NWS Great Falls MT
entry.summary: Snow will begin this evening around Marias Pass and adjacent areas, largely remaining light at the pass through Thursday afternoon. Total snow accumulation in grassy areas of a few inches will be possible, with lesser amounts on paved surfaces. Snow in excess of 6 inches is forecast above pass level. Hence, those with outdoor plans in the high terrain should be prepared for snowy and cold conditions.
Monitoring message only. Please disregard.

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued November 13 at 3:20PM EST by NWS Albany NY
entry.summary:
Fuels remain very dry across southern Vermont according to the Vermont Department of Forests, Parks and Recreation. This, combined with low relative humidity values of 20 to 30 percent during the midday hours on Thursday, could contribute to faster ignitions and increased rate of fire spread. It is recommended to avoid activities that could create a spark.
For more information about the current fire danger rating, any burn restrictions, and wildfire prevention and education, please visit your state forestry or environmental protection website.

entry.title: High Surf Advisory issued November 13 at 12:14PM PST until November 13 at 9:00PM PST by NWS Los Angeles/Oxnard CA
entry.summary:
* WHAT...Large breaking waves of 10 to 15 feet, highest on west and northwest-facing beaches. There will be widespread dangerous rip currents.
* WHERE...San Luis Obispo County Beaches and Santa Barbara County Central Coast Beaches.
* WHEN...Until 9 PM PST this evening.
* IMPACTS...There is an increased risk for ocean drowning. Rip currents can pull swimmers and surfers out to sea. Large breaking waves can cause injury, wash people off beaches and rocks, and capsize small boats near shore.
* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Minor coastal flooding is possible on west and northwest-facing beaches a couple of hours on either side of the high tide this morning, which is around 720 AM PST.

entry.title: Flood Advisory issued November 13 at 12:07PM PST until November 13 at 3:15PM PST by NWS Seattle WA

* WHERE...Portions of northwest and west central Washington, including the following counties, in northwest Washington, Island, Jefferson, Kitsap and Mason. In west central Washington, King, Pierce, Snohomish and Thurston.
* WHEN...Until 315 PM PST.
* IMPACTS...Minor flooding in low-lying and poor drainage areas. Ponding of water in urban or other areas is occurring or is imminent.
* ADDITIONAL DETAILS... - At 1205 PM PST, Doppler radar indicated heavy rain. Minor flooding is ongoing or expected to begin shortly in the advisory area. entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued November 14 at 4:25AM ChST by NWS Tiyan GU
entry.summary:
Tropical Storm Man-yi will be passing just north of Yap, Ulithi and Fais today. ASCAT shows that, as expected, the south side of the storm is weaker. Nevertheless, windy conditions with occasional gale force gusts can be expected across all 3 of these islands as Man-yi passes just to the north. Also, after Man-yi passes by, southeast winds flowing into Man-yi will keep the winds and gusts elevated to just below damaging levels Friday.

Gusts will be especially prevalent near these showers, which will help to mix down higher winds aloft. After Friday, conditions will start to normalize as Man-yi passes north of Palau. For today, tonight and Friday, take any necessary action to protect crops or other property vulnerable to high winds across these islands.
